{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1d44e0ca-fcd9-4940-ba93-11d2a70600be","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n\n<!-- Include a README in the package -->\n<ItemGroup>\n  <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\n### Key properties explained\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a .NET tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `PackageId` | The NuGet package name users install with `dotnet tool install` |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. No special runtime or hosting config is needed — `PackAsTool` + `Exe` output type handles everything.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0f174d68-8f23-4170-b1d5-ac79641616d5","outputTokens":537},"id":"6ceb1592-dc6d-4e45-8050-f0aca3f56651","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:53:31.298Z","parentId":"6620fbda-4516-48bd-afc8-7b414707f2f0"}
